*****
[2] Kenya - Alerts, ministries of Agriculture and Health
Date: Tue 22 May 2018, 9:05 AM
Source: Standard Media [edited]
https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001281290/alert-over-possible-rift-valley-fever-outbreak


An alert has been issued over the possible outbreak of RVF in parts of the country due to the ongoing rains. The alert from the ministries of Health and Agriculture named 15 counties as high-risk areas.

The notice was signed by Director of Veterinary Services Obadiah Njagi and his Health counterpart, Jackson Kioko. According to Dr. Njagi, there was increased risk of RVF due to increased cases of flooding. He noted that flooding not only caused displacement of people and animals but also increased the risk of diseases transmitted by mosquitoes such as RVF; "a viral disease of livestock which also affects human beings if they get into contact with blood or tissues from infected animals," he said.

Njagi noted that certain groups, such as herders, slaughterhouse workers, farmers and veterinarians, were at higher risk of getting infected. "The virus can be transmitted to humans through the handling of animal tissue during slaughtering, during births or while conducting veterinary procedures," he said. He added that the last outbreak of the disease was recorded during the El Nino rains in 2006/2007, where around 160 people died and Sh4 billion [39 million USD] loss was recorded in the livestock sector.

And Dr. Kioko called on the public to be cautious and stop slaughtering livestock at home without veterinary inspection. He advised the public to use protective gear while assisting livestock give birth or while removing stillbirths. He added that slaughtering or consuming food from sick or dead animals should be avoided and all suspicious deaths of livestock reported to relevant offices.

"We are asking the public to use treated mosquito nets and repellants to keep away the insects that easily spread the virus mainly in flooded areas," he said. Kioko further advised those who get a fever to report to the nearest health centre for treatment. "To help in early detection and response in case of a disease outbreak, all reports of sudden deaths and abortions in livestock should be reported to the nearest veterinary offices for action," he said.

[Byline: Antony Gitonga]

